<span id="fn_895"></span>[198:5](sbe31023.htm#fr_898.md) See the Âfrînagân.

<span id="fn_896"></span>[198:6](sbe31023.htm#fr_899.md) The rutting
season.

<span id="fn_897"></span>[198:7](sbe31023.htm#fr_900.md) Haug first called
attention to the striking coincidence with the Indian. In the Aitareya
and *S*atapatha Brâhma*n*as, in the Atharvaveda, and in the Râmâya*n*a,
the gods are brought up to the number thirty-three. The names differ
somewhat however. (See Essays, ed. West, 2nd edition, p. 276; see also
*R*v. 240, 9; 250, 2.)

<span id="fn_898"></span>[199:1](sbe31023.htm#fr_901.md) The star Jupiter
has been called Ormuzd by the Persians and Armenians, and it may be
intended here, as stars are next mentioned, but who can fail to be
struck with the resemblance to the Mitra-Varu*n*a of the *Ri*g-veda.
Possibly both ideas were present to the composer.

<span id="fn_899"></span>[199:2](sbe31023.htm#fr_902.md) Recall *K*akshur
Mitrasya Varu*n*asya Agne*h*.

<span id="fn_900"></span>[199:3](sbe31023.htm#fr_903.md) The first day of
