<span id="fn_913"></span>[201:3](sbe31023.htm#fr_916.md) The divine Order
par eminence, expressed in the ritual and the faith.

<span id="fn_914"></span>[201:4](sbe31023.htm#fr_917.md) Not 'to the chief
of Hâvani,' possibly 'in the lordship,' the time when it is especially
the object of worship. Thus each object of worship becomes in its turn a
'lord or chief' of 'the ritual order.'

<span id="fn_915"></span>[201:5](sbe31023.htm#fr_918.md) The soul of the
celebrant or his client is intended.

<span id="fn_916"></span>[202:1](sbe31023.htm#fr_919.md) Compare *R*v. VII,
86, 3-6.

<span id="fn_917"></span>[202:2](sbe31023.htm#fr_920.md) Practised, or
induced neglect, or omitted portions of it.

<span id="fn_918"></span>[202:3](sbe31023.htm#fr_921.md) 'I invite for
Thee' (?).

<span id="fn_919"></span>[202:4](sbe31023.htm#fr_922.md) That the thought,
word, and deed here were more than the mere semi-mechanical use of
faculties in reciting the liturgy, is clear. At the same time all
morality was supposed to be represented in the liturgy. The evil man
would offend in thought, word, and deed, if he recited it carelessly, or
with bad conscience, and as guilty of any known and unrepented sins. The
moral and ceremonial laws went hand in hand.

